{
  "texts": [
    "More centrally there are numerous clusters dominated by different types of stroma (Fig. 3B, left) and stroma-rich tumor, with greater or lesser degrees of inflammation, and different qualities of extracellular matrix.",
    "The remaining clusters mostly define various recognisable manifestations of adenocarcinoma (Fig. 4A).",
    "Clusters characterised by all 6 classical patterns are identified.",
    "Lepidic-enriched clusters also contained numerous tiles histopathologically judged to be acinar or papillary in nature, highlighting current difficulties in histopathological identification of lowgrade invasive disease 52.",
    "The 'lepidic' cluster with thinner septa is close to mucinous disease in the UMAP (HPC 28), while the other, with bulkier interstitium, is close to reactive and inflamed normal lung clusters (HPC 37)."
  ]
}